		<description><![CDATA[(This is a personal reflection on the second and third day of the YAPC Europe 2011, it is not intended to be a guide to what was on or a significant critique of the event, it is just a personal journal). Day Two Day Two of YAPC was started by Alexei who quickly welcomed us [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>(This is a personal reflection on the second and third day of the YAPC Europe 2011, it is not intended to be a guide to what was on or a significant critique of the event, it is just a personal journal).</p>
<h2>Day Two</h2>
<p>Day Two of YAPC was started by Alexei who quickly welcomed us all and then introduced Damian Conway who was talking about converting some of his Perl 5 modules to work with Perl 6. Damian is a witty, engaging and experienced speaker and it shows in his delivery style and the quality of his talk and slides. he makes the whole process of presenting look effortless. Of course, if you had attended his talk on presentations you would know that he had already practiced his talk at least three times in the week of the YAPC, that was an important lesson and it does help as it makes you confident and knowledgable about the flow of your talk. There were several other tricks that Damian gave in that presentation and if you get a chance to attend a lesson in Speaking I recommend you take it (though Damian would probably chase me with a recursive stick if I didn&#8217;t point out that there were five things to remember from his presentation and that knowing there were five was one of the five).</p>
<div id="attachment_1325" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 510px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1325" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/24/ye2011days-two-and-three/yapc21/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1325 " title="A Gaggle of Attendees" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/yapc21-300x120.jpg" alt="A Gaggle of Attendees" width="500" height="200" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A Gaggle of Attendees</p></div>
<p>Damian&#8217;s central message was clear, he has been able to successfully update and/or reproduce some of his modules in Perl 5 in Perl 6 and it presented a learning process. He also had some excellent metaphors using popular sic-fi (which was lost on the likes of Tux and Smylers), to illustrate the relationship between Perl 5&#038;6 and CPAN (being a Star Wars fan more than a Trek fan i appreciated those gags the most).</p>
<h3>Mojo (not Jojo)</h3>
<p>I went to see Marcus talking on Mojolicious, this is a project that gives a different way of working in Perl and is an important project in bringing new people to Perl. My loss at this conference was in missing the Dancer talks as I wanted to hear more about this project as well as it is also a great new Perl project that is getting a lot of attention and support. Marcus gave a good introduction to the history and manner of Mojolicious and the way in which you can manage project development using the various tools and plugins.</p>
<h3>Mark Keating = marketing</h3>
<p>Then it was my talk. I was nervous giving my talk as it was the first time I had spoken about marketing since taking on my new role and I knew a lot of people were curious as to what I had done and where we are going. Hopefully I have started to show the way we need to take and that my message about all of us joining in was conveyed. Also I hope I gave enough praise to all those people (davorg, getty, Gabor, Ranguard, JJ, Barbie, Karen Pauley, Obra amongst others) who have already been doing a great job thus far. It is easy to look and say we need to do &#8220;x&#8221; or there should be more &#8220;y&#8221; but saying something and doing something are polar opposites and the people who have been chugging away at the mammoth task need to be held up and recognised as they are setting the high standard we all have to follow.</p>
<p>I received some feedback about my talk which was encouraging, also Josette and Marc Chantreaux (French Perler) asked if I could write out the talk so that it could be translated/used by non-native English speakers who would have some trouble understanding my accent and the fact that I talk a little too fast. Josette has offered to put the text on her blog (with me being a guest blogger) so you can expect there to be some rambling discursive in the near future, I promise not to be terse or concise as that would break a trend.</p>
<p>Once again I was involved in a number of conversations about marketing including talking to the members of Net-a-Porter &#8211; it is possible we may be able to put together an event using NAP and maybe one using LoveFilm in London in the near future. My conversation with NAP was about the big news of the day that I would be involved with by making sure the TPF site was uptodate at the time of the announcement (see below).</p>
<p>The Lightning Talks on day Two lived up to the fun of day one and again there were some announcements, the biggest of which was Karen announcing the generous donation of $10,000 (USD) to P5 CMF (Perl 5 Core Maintenance Fund) by NAP. This was then surpassed (for me at least as I love these two people and if you do Perl in Europe you know and love them also) when Liz and Wendy announced they would also be giving $5,000 to this important project. The fund is in full swing now and hopefully we can maintain a pace of donations.</p>
<h3>Food and talk</h3>
<p>Today was the day of the attendees dinner and we went to the Ludo for some traditional and non-traditional Latvian food and drinks. Once again I managed to talk to lots of great people and got a quick word about next years QA Conference with Daxim and put forward my thoughts about the hosting and running of the event and how I might be able to help. QA is a great  conference/hackathon idea and needs a lot of support. In the Perl world we can now be a little blase about our testing culture as we have CPAN Testers who run tests on 23,000 modules, have passed over 14 million tests and I believe will pass/have passed 1 million tests in a single month (August). But our relaxed attitude is built on the strengths of events like QA and CPAN Testers and any event that promotes furthers that cause is worthwhile.</p>
<div id="attachment_1326" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 310px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1326" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/24/ye2011days-two-and-three/yapc22/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1326" title="Perl people take everything very seriously" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/yapc22-300x182.jpg" alt="Perl people take everything very seriously" width="300" height="182" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Perl people take everything very seriouslyq</p></div>
<p>The evening finished with me speaking to Barbie and JJ about Perl and life in general and then celebrating Getty&#8217;s news (as Community Manager for DDG) with Marcus and others.</p>
<h2>Day Three</h2>
<p>I skipped this mornings keynote, which is a shame as I really wanted to see it, but I also needed to talk to Josette, Wendy and Liz and to work out some writing I needed to do. I always feel bad going into someones talk and just ignoring them to do some writing, especially if it is someone I want to listen to as I feel I am doing two jobs badly (that&#8217;s not to say that I haven&#8217;t done that, but I really didn&#8217;t want to do it to Jesse!).</p>
<p>I managed to get myself sorted to go and listen to Matt speaking about DBIx::Class and in particular the current work to evolve the project. He did this by giving an overview of the whole history of Dbic so that the audience knew how and why the decisions that were made came to be.</p>
<div id="attachment_1327" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 210px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1327" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/24/ye2011days-two-and-three/yapc23/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1327" title="Matt talks on Dbic" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/yapc23-200x300.jpg" alt="Matt talks on Dbic" width="200" height="300" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Matt talks on Dbic</p></div>
<h3>Loving my Community</h3>
<p>After lunch I gave my second (third if we count my lightning talk on day one) talk of the conference. This time I was talking on how &#8220;I <3 my Community". I have presented this talk before at Perl Oasis and at NWE Technical Meeting, but I updated it for this conference. I may do a sequel to this talk as it is good fun and I think I can use a different anecdote and social model to talk about the community. It is also a chance to mention all the people that inspire me and I like and/or respect (and at this point I must shout "I <3 RIBASUSHI" and I hope he gets the message <img src='http://mdk.per.ly/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' />  ).</p>
<p>Once my talks were done with I felt much more relaxed. Actually during my talk I was feeling quite chilled, I have done the talk twice previously, I liked the subject and I had done as Damian suggested and rehearsed at least three times and I felt "like a lion" (and now that's 4 of the things that I learned from him mentioned). I also didn't stand behind my laptop as a shield but moved about and held the stage (there we go, that's another).</p>
<h3>End times</h3>
<p>As the conference was heading to a close I was starting to feel a little mournful. I had attended a good number of talks, but I felt it was not enough. I had talked to a good number of people but I wished I had spoken to more. I did feel that I had made progress in my personal development and thinking about subjects, and been inspired by the people I had spoken to and this was very encouraging.</p>
<p>Soon it was time for the final set of lightning talks and as usual they were of a very high quality. During the talks we had several great announcements. Brian d. foy presented the White Camel awards to Andrew Shitov, Leo Lapworth and Daisuke Maki, Salve from Oslo Perl Mongers announced that this Monger group would be donating 1,000 euros to the P5 CMF. As with Net-A-Porter I had prior notice of this, from Salve, so was ready to retweet his live tweet on the subject and to put a small thanks on the front page of the TPF site. It is really amazing that another Perl Monger group have made a generous contribution to the fund.</p>
<div id="attachment_1328" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 310px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1328" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/24/ye2011days-two-and-three/yapc24/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1328" title="Matt's 'State of the Velociraptor' discusses vital things" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/yapc24-300x200.jpg" alt="Matt's 'State of the Velociraptor' discusses vital things" width="300" height="200" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Matt's 'State of the Velociraptor' discusses vital things</p></div>
<p>Matt rounded off the conference with another State of the Velociraptor talk on the events happening in the Perl 5 world and was followed across the Atlantic by several soft toys that were once again used as projectiles.</p>
<h2>Ending&#8230;</h2>
<p>After the event it was time to say goodbye to Riga, I didn&#8217;t go to the after conference drinking as I needed to get some rest and put some thoughts down on paper. I did however manage to have a good meal with some of the other attendees, so thanks to Ribasushi, Ilmari, JJL, MST and Getty for joining me at dinner.</p>
<p>A big round of thanks should be given to the conference organisers, Andrew Shitov &#8211; Dan Makarov &#8211; Alex Kapranov &#8211; Dmitry Karasik &#8211; Sergey Zhavoronkov &#8211; for putting on a truly great event. This year saw a good number of new attendees along with a lot of familiar faces and it was good to be a part of it. Now we have a year to wait and prepare for the fun and excitement that will be YAPC::EU::2012::Frankfurt.</p>
<div id="attachment_1329" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 310px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1329" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/24/ye2011days-two-and-three/yapc25/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1329" title="Frankfurt 2012" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/yapc25-300x200.jpg" alt="Frankfurt 2012" width="300" height="200" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Frankfurt 2012</p></div>
]]></content:encoded>
