		<description><![CDATA[There are going to be blogs about YAPCEU, already Leon has done a report on his Day One that is far nicer than what I would have written, I just wanted to do an interim report on what I have seen, been doing. I arrived early on Day One and was greeted by the usual [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="attachment_1303" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 292px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1303" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/16/ye2011day-one/img_3010/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1303" title="YAPC EU Logo" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/IMG_3010-282x300.jpg" alt="YAPC EU Logo" width="282" height="300" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">YAPC EU Logo</p></div>
<p>There are going to be blogs about <a href="http://yapceurope.lv/ye2011/">YAPCEU</a>, already <a href="http://blogs.perl.org/users/acme/2011/08/yapceurope-2011-day-1.html">Leon</a> has done a report on his Day One that is far nicer than what I would have written, I just wanted to do an interim report on what I have seen, been doing.</p>
<div id="attachment_1301" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 310px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1301" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/16/ye2011day-one/img_2988/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1301" title="Queues marvelous queues..." src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/IMG_2988-300x200.jpg" alt="Queues marvelous queues..." width="300" height="200" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Queues marvelous queues...</p></div>
<p>I arrived early on Day One and was greeted by the usual long conference queue for registration and sign-up. That was fun to view and I grabbed a sticker from one of the people already signed up and hand wrote my name onto it so that I wouldn&#8217;t have to instantly sign in and could do it later.</p>
<p>Andrew Shitov started the ball rolling by welcoming us all to the conference and then introducing the next year&#8217;s YAPC::EU winners.</p>
<p>Well you probably all know by now that next years YAPC::EU will be held in the wonderful city of Frankfurt in Germany, sorry that Sofia lost out but also slightly pleased as it is closer and I know many people who will be able to make it just because of the central location. Hopefully Sophia will once again bid and get this event at a future date.</p>
<div id="attachment_1302" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 310px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1302" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/16/ye2011day-one/img_3001/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1302" title="YAPC::EU::2012 orgas receive their kickstart donation" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/IMG_3001-300x200.jpg" alt="YAPC::EU::2012 orgas receive their kickstart donation" width="300" height="200" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">YAPC::EU::2012 orgas receive their kickstart donation</p></div>
<p>I saw Larry&#8217;s keynote, he spoke on modernism and post-modernism and in respect to that he mentioned Architecture, Music, Literature and I love art. Larry was being wonderfully discursive and used a lot of individual perspectives on those areas and punctuated his talk with many great pictures of Riga and started a meme about Piranha Ducks. It has been a couple of years since I saw a keynote from Larry and it is nice to know that this one will vary so much from his OSCON and YAPC::NA talks that it is worth seeking out recordings of those.</p>
<p>Matt gave an interesting talk on Philosophy and documentation and I managed to see a great talk on HTML 5 before lunch.</p>
<p>At lunch I was talking to Barbie about the CPAN Testers and catching up with him and then JJ (Jon Allen) found me with an apology for not being in touch as he has been very busy with moving house so hasn&#8217;t been able to catch up, added to that I think I was bouncing into his Spam box with my messages. JJ and I then went and found a quiet space and we, well I say we it was mostly JJ, went and further updated the <a href="http://www.perlfoundation.org">TPF website</a> which is now looking much shinier and JJ also updated the small style changes I wanted into the other sites so we have a consistency of design.</p>
<div id="attachment_1304" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 310px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1304" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/16/ye2011day-one/img_3018/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1304" title="Wes Johnson gives his first talk and is up first" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/IMG_3018-300x201.jpg" alt="Wes Johnson gives his first talk and is up first" width="300" height="201" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Wes Johnson gives his first talk and is up first</p></div>
<p>The Lightning Talks were the usual fun, I was up third after Wes Johnson, who was giving his first ever talk at a Perl Conference and was up in front of everyone as first LT speaker, he was very nervous but delivered an excellent presentation on the GCI. So a future speaker is born, I hope he comes back with a longer talk for next year or maybe he can be persuaded to run the effort for GCI next year.</p>
<p>My Lightning talk was on An Armful of Announcements. Firstly I spoke about the GSoC and in particular how the efforts of rafl, the students and the mentors (with particular reference on the organisational efforts of rafl) have resulted in a 100% success for us this year. Then I spoke on <a href="http://www.send-a-newbie.enlightenedperl.org/">Send-A-Newbie</a> and the efforts for this year and next year, I mentioned the <a href="http://conferences.yapceurope.org/lpw2011/">London Perl Workshop </a>and the plans to do more training at the event and finally spoke about the need for people to start a grass roots movement to <a href="http://www.perlfoundation.org/press_releases">distribute flyers</a> and material about Perl that I will be continuing this year.</p>
<div class="mceTemp mceIEcenter">
<dl id="attachment_1305" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 310px;">
<dt class="wp-caption-dt"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1305" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/08/16/ye2011day-one/img_3035/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1305 " title="Dave Cross's: A Modest Proposal" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/08/IMG_3035-300x200.jpg" alt="Dave Cross's: A Modest Proposal" width="300" height="200" /></a></dt>
</dl>
</div>
<p>One of the best, and most controversial it seems, Lightning Talks was Dave Cross&#8217; wonderful A Modest Proposal. DC was nicely running a Swiftian satire on the state of the Perlverse, it was fun for me as he used the marketing-&gt;Mark Keating transformation and the great line &#8220;Say no to marketing and say yes to Perl Masons&#8221;. The notion that we go underground and run hidden Perl clubs is so much fun and nicely acts as the antithesis to what we should really be doing. So Swift-The Masons-Fight Club all nicely mocked and homaged.</p>
<p>After this I had a few more conversations with Karen, Abigail and Ribasushi and then headed back to the hotel to do some $work, some TPF matters and to rehearse my talk for the next day.</p>
<p>I also posted some<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/29379919@N07/sets/72157627440577026/"> images from the conference here on Flickr</a>.</p>
<p>-mdk = Day One over</p>
]]></content:encoded>
