			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="float: right; margin: 8px; width: 150px;"><br />
<a title="The Perl Foundation" href="http://www.facebook.com/tpf.perl" target="_TOP">The Perl Foundation</a><br />
<a title="The Perl Foundation" href="http://www.facebook.com/tpf.perl" target="_TOP"><img style="border: 0px;" src="http://badge.facebook.com/badge/213296278682699.2549.1757479420.png" alt="" width="120" height="259" /></a><br />
<a title="The Perl Foundation" href="http://www.facebook.com/tpf.perl" target="_TOP">Perl GSoC</a><br />
<a title="Perl - Google Summer of Code" href="http://www.facebook.com/pages/Perl-Google-Summer-of-Code/200130976674239" target="_TOP"><img style="border: 0px;" src="http://badge.facebook.com/badge/200130976674239.1996.18876661.png" alt="" width="120" height="247" /></a><br />
</span></p>
<p>Before we begin I just wish to state that I haven&#8217;t gone insane I just have channeled the spirit of Baden Powell and am working in advance so that we can function efficiently later this year. So I am proud to present to you the current working copy of the Google Summer of Code flyer for Perl projects next year (and in fact this can be used in subsequent years).</p>
<h2>Choosing the look</h2>
<p>I would like to note a few of the decisions that affected the design:</p>
<p>1. The Google Logo is not released for usage, Google vigorously protect their brand image and don&#8217;t authorise its usage even in pargtner events such as the GSoC, unique branding is usually created for that purpose. For this reason I chose a similar but not same as font for the text and made no attempt to use the colour look;</p>
<p>2. Because of the above Google usually create a different logo/branding for each year&#8217;s GSoC, this year for instance has a faint Tron Legacy feel to it. This means that a standard look cannot be applied to any visual elements that will fit into the yearly theme, yet we must promote early if we are to increase the number of people who are aware of the scheme and wish to participate in it on behalf of Perl;</p>
<p>3. Any colours had to be evocative to the subject yet also be in keeping with the other logo elements that would be eventually placed upon the page;</p>
<p>4. Any block text had to be succinct and short, to grab attention and to ease in the translation.</p>
<p>The final poster looks like this:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>
<div id="attachment_1172" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 415px"><a rel="attachment wp-att-1172" href="http://mdk.per.ly/2011/06/21/gsoc-next-years-flyer/english-pages-basic-2/"><img class="size-large wp-image-1172  " title="GSoC Perl Flyer for 2012+" src="http://mdk.per.ly/files/2011/06/english-pages-basic1-563x800.jpg" alt="GSoC Perl Flyer for 2012+" width="405" height="576" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">GSoC Perl Flyer for 2012+</p></div>
<h2 style="text-align: left;">In Other Words&#8230;</h2>
<p style="text-align: left;">So, we now come to the task that the worldwide Perl community can help me with. In order to get as many prospective students onto the program for Perl in 2012 we will need to do two things:</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">1. The poster will need to be translated in to other languages to spread the message, although a good level of English is usually found amongst computer programmers/students it is still good to spread the marketing word in the local languuage. So if you can translate the simple text on this flyer then please contact me.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">2. I will need volunteers who are willing to print a few flyers off and distribute them at schools/colleges/universities by using mailing boards, pigeon holes and putting them on desks/buses if needed. So if you are a member of a local PM group, or a Perl person who can do this then please contact me so that I can build a list of people and places we are distributing to.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Thanks in advance.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">-mdk</p>
]]></content:encoded>
